PERTUSSIS - USA EX RUSSIA (03)
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Mon, 13 May 2002 13:25:09 -0400
From: Robert Steinglass <rsteinglass@basics.org>

I am replying to your posting on pertussis in Russia. I worked in 11
countries of the former Soviet Union, including Russia, starting from 1992
until 1999 to provide technical support for vaccination programs. This
work was funded by USAID and carried out by the REACH and BASICS projects.

It will come as a surprise to most of your readers that most of the
countries of the former Soviet Union do not collect data on coverage with
"DPT". It is true that when reporting to international agencies, they
report their coverage invariably as DPT. However, these countries
internally reported, and most still report, coverage separately by each
specific antigen: that is, coverage with D, P, and T.

In the case of Russia, the difference between reported coverage with D and
coverage with P was significant, as much as 15 absolute percentage points
in the late 1980s and early 1990s. This disparity reflected the concerns
typically heard from pediatricians that the DPT vaccine was "too strong"
and the children had become "too weak" to be able to tolerate the pertussis
component of DPT. Consequently, many providers opted to use DT (and even Td
!!) for pediatric immunization. Practitioners in the USA need to make
careful evaluation of adopted children's vaccination records to determine
whether or not they indeed received the pertussis component.

The countries of the former Soviet Union also never reported coverage on
children under 12 months of age, which is the international standard. While
the countries of the former Soviet Union had an excellent system of
tracking individual children in need of vaccination by pediatric catchment
areas, they did not adopt this global standard of monitoring and reporting
vaccination coverage by 12 months of age. Instead the numerator to
calculate coverage typically included children irrespective of age of
vaccination and the denominator excluded the sizeable number of children
with permanent or temporary contraindications to vaccination. Consequently,
timely vaccination coverage was (and is) considerably less well reported in
many of these countries. In fact, as part of their applications for funding
from GAVI (the Global Alliance for Vaccines and Immunization), several of
the former Soviet countries conducted population-based 30-cluster
vaccination coverage surveys. These surveys have all shown coverage by 12
months of age to be about 20 percent (or more in some cases) lower than the
reported figures.

Each of these surveys also shows that the mean age of DPT vaccination is
quite delayed, most likely due to the frequency of temporary contraindications.

Much of our work in collaboration with WHO was devoted to exposing these
new countries to recent developments in western science to guide policy
reformulation, to encourage them to streamline their immunization
schedules, to reduce their excessive lists of contraindications, and to
establish active monitoring systems (in Kyrgyzstan and Ukraine) so that
health workers at all levels could indeed start to track their cumulative
monthly DPT coverage in infants. In most of the other countries of the
former Soviet Union, coverage is still monitored in the former Soviet
fashion as described above.
--
Robert Steinglass
Immunization Team Leader
BASICS
1600 Wilson Blvd., Suite 300
Arlington, VA. 22209
USA
<rsteingl@basics.org>

[Thank you very much for this clarification Robert. As someone who had
worked fairly extensively in vaccination program activities internationally
(but never in the Russian Federation), I still was unaware that the
pertussis component had been optionally removed as part of routine
vaccination activities in that region. Hence, it is possible that many of
the children coming from the Russian Federation are behind in the pertussis
vaccine component and that a careful review of the vaccination histories
might identify this. The additional information that many children's
vaccinations are delayed for "temporary reasons" may also explain the lower
coverages. Adjusting the reported coverage of 97 percent for the
information from the coverage surveys would have the DPT coverages by age
12 months to be approximately 77 percent overall, and indicative of the
need to improve vaccination activities, as well as highlighting the need to
carefully screen vaccination histories of children coming from the Russian
Federation. - Mod.MPP]

