Date: Mon, 13 May 2002 15:11:02 -0400
From: Sharon Ludwig <SLudwig@comdt.uscg.mil>

Although the immunization records of internationally adopted children are
carefully reviewed by the US Embassy and INS officials, the children are
often routinely completely re-vaccinated when they visit their primary care
physician in the US. The same goes for pre-adoption screening for HIV,
Hepatitis B, and TB. CF: Aronson, Jane, "Medical Evaluation and
Infectious Considerations on Arrival" in "Medical Issues in International
Adoptions," Pediatric Annals 29:4/April 2000

Apparently, the prevailing belief is that the records may be inaccurate and
the original records cannot be read by officials in US public schools (and
copies may not be considered official). It is simpler and safer to
revaccinate, even though it is rather traumatic for the already
culture-shocked little new arrivals.
--
Sharon L. Ludwig, MD MPH MA
Commander, US Public Health Service
Chief, Operational Preventive Medicine/
Disease Control Epidemiology
US Coast Guard Commandant (G-WKH-1)
2100 Second Street SW
Washington, DC 20593
<sludwig@comdt.uscg.mil>

[Taking into consideration the information given by Robert Steinglass
above, it does not appear to be unwise to consider revaccination as
mentioned here. - Mod.MPP]

