Date: Sat, 11 May 2002 09:25:56 -0500
From: R&M Whitworth <rmwhit@aaahawk.com>

I write regarding the vaccination of adoptive children and the review of
immunization records prior to traveling to the adopted (or to be adopted)
child's country of origin. While every attempt is made to understand the
adoptive child's health and needs before traveling, certain cultural
differences, as well as governmental procedures, preclude obtaining all
information one would like to have. The INS does require adoptive parents
to obtain all immunizations, or start obtaining them, within the first 30
days after returning to the United States.

The American Medical Association also recommends that, in most cases, all
internationally adopted children repeat their immunization series once in
the US. (This was recently reported in the MMWR)
--
Randy G. Whitworth, R.Ph.
Clinical Pharmacist
(and father to one girl from China, traveling in 3 days for the second)
<rmwhit@aaahawk.com>

[The MMWR issue mentioned by Randy G. Whitworth is: General Recommendations
on Immunization: Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization
Practices (ACIP) and the American Academy of Family Physicians (AAFP). 8
Feb 2002. 51 (RR02);1-36
<http://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/rr5102a1.htm>

