[4]
Date: Mon, 13 May 2002 09:44:20 -0400
From: ProMED-mail subscriber who wishes name to be withheld

The moderator posed the question about "whether vaccination histories
of adoptive children should be reviewed prior to travel to their adoptive
country."

They are! As a US parent of a child adopted from a Russian orphanage, I
can attest to the mountains of paperwork required and reviewed. The
immunization history is reviewed by a physician during the medical exam
required to obtain a visa. Additionally, in order to obtain a visa, parents
of young children must sign an affidavit that they will update and complete
vaccinations upon return to the US. No measure will be 100 percent
effective, but the mechanism for review of vaccine history is in place.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Clearly there are regulations in place that would ensure that adopted
children are appropriately vaccinated for age prior to obtaining a visa for
entry to the USA. But, as pointed out, no measure is 100 percent. The
reference kindly provided by Dr. Sharon Ludwick demonstrates that the
pediatric community has recognized the special circumstances related to
international adoptions. Having gotten the predicted barrage of emails in
response to my comments, I think it's now time to cut this thread. - Mod.MPP]
